TICKS IN MADAGASCAR? (02)
=========================
[see: Ticks in Madagascar? 970517222528.
A quick perusal of the 4 posting below indicates that ticks do exist in
Madagascar, which was the query in the original posting. - mod. p.c.]
[1]
Date: Sun, 18 May 1997 17:13:22 GMT
From: gratz@ibm.net (Norman Gratz)
Here are some references from my database re ticks & lemur in Madagascar.
Contact the Institute pasteur in Anntanarivo, they will also have information.
References:
Rodhain F. Petter J J. Albignac R. Coulanges P. Hannoun C.
Arboviruses and lemurs in Madagascar: Experimental infection of Lemur
fulvus with yellow fever and west nile viruses
Am J Trop Med Hyg 34(4):816-822
1985 Madagascar
*:Antibodies have frequently been detected to flaviviruses in lemurs.
Experimental infections with YF & WNV were performed. Infections resulting
were inapparent with a 3-4 day long viremia for YF & 4-6 with WN. Authors
conclude that lemurs could act as amlifying hosts for WN virus if it were
introduced & hosts for YF if introduced. Brief dicussion of Aedes
potential vectors. (8 refs)
Fontenille D Mathiot C Coulanges P.
Les virus de fievres hemorragiques a Madagascar
Ann Inst Pasteur madagascar 54(1):117-124
1988 Madagascar
Aedes aegypti Rattus rattus Rattus norvegicus
arboviruses rodent borne diseases haemorrhagic fevers HFRS
RVF HFRS Yellow fever CCHF
*:CCHF, HFRS RVF are prsent in Madagascar. YF has never been reported.
Mathiot C C Fountenille D Digoutte J P Coulanges P
First isolation of Congo-Crimean Haemorrhagic fever in Madagascar
Ann Inst Pasteur Virol 139:239-241
1988 Madagascar
Amblyomma variegatum Boophilus microplus
arboviruses haemorrhagic fevers tick borne diseases tic CCHF
*:5 strains of CCHF were isolated from ticks taken from beef carcasses at a
slaughter house. This appears to be the first isolation of the virus from
the country.
Mathiot C C Fontenille D Georges A J Coulanges P
Antibodies to haemorrhagic fever viruses in Madagascar.
Trans Roy Soc Trop Med Hyg 83:407-409
1989 Madagascar
Boophilus microplus Mastomys sp Praomys sp
arenaviruses haemorrhagic fevers filoviruses
CCHF RVF Ebola Lassa fever Marburg
*:381 adults tested by IIF for antibodies against Ebola, Lassa, CCHF and
RVF. Highest prev. to Ebola=3D4.5% [I have left this unedited but am sure
this is a computer translation error of some kind. Mod. pc]. Possibly a
less pathogenic strain forund
on the island as no sevre symptoms seen. In absence of Mastomys and
Praomys on island, no surprise that there was no Lassa. CCF and RVF
relatively low. Also no reactions to Marburg.
Rodhain F Fontenille D
La recurrente a tiques Malagache: une affection eradique?
Bull Soc Path Exot 82:192-198 1989 Madagascar
Ornithodoros moubata Borrelia duttoni
tick borne diseases ticks
relapsing fever
*:Authors believe that relapsing fever caused by B. duttoni has disappeared
from the country as no cases have been reported for 30 years. The vector
has also become very rare and people did not recognize the tick. Authors
believe that the reduction in the growing of pigs and the house-spraying by
the mosquito vector control programmes are the reason for the disappearence
of the Borellia. (13 refs)
--
Dr. Norman Gratz
gratz@ibm.net
