[2]
Date: Mon, 19 May 1997 11:06:03 +0000
From: Colin Leake <colin.leake@lshtm.ac.uk>
There certainly are ticks on Madagascar - a staightforward Medline search
picks out over 20 references over the last 30 years or so. The argasid
_Ornithodorus moubata_ is present and a number of hard tick genera,
Boophilus, Haemaphysalis, Amblyomma and Ixodes.
Particularly useful references would appear to be:
Fontenille et al 1985, Archives Institute Pasteur Madagascar 52 171- 80 and
1984 51. 161-202. Hoogstraal 1973 J Parasitol. 59 1099-1117.
--
Colin Leake
London School of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene
<colin.leake@lshtm.ac.uk>
*****
[3]
Date: Mon, 19 May 1997 12:17:59 -0400
From: Tom Schwan <TSCHWAN@atlas.niaid.nih.gov>
There are ticks on the island of Madagascar and other islands in the
Malagasy region.
See: Harry Hoogstraal, 1953, Ticks (Ixodoidea) of the Malagasy Faunal
Region (excepting the Seychelles), Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative
Zoology at Harvard College, Vol III, No. 2: 37-113. This work discusses
both native and introduced species.
--
Tom G. Schwan
Rocky Mountain Laboratories
NIAID, NIH
Hamilton, MT 59840
******
[4]

Date: Mon, 19 May 1997 08:43:40 -0500
From: "Dr. Norman Ronald" <n-ronald@TVMDL.TAMU.EDU>
There are no listings for tick borne diseases of man for Madagascar. Q
fever has been reported there but I suspect the transmission was by routes
other than tick borne. I suspect there may be host specific ticks such as
_Boophilus microplus_ which have been introduced to the island.
N.C. Ronald PhD
Texas Veterinary Medical Diagnostic Laboratory
"Dr. Norman Ronald" <n-ronald@TVMDL.TAMU.EDU>
